Biography of Zhang Shizhi and Feng Tang

Zhang Tingwei Shizhi was a native of Duyang, with the courtesy name Ji. He had an elder brother named Zhong with whom he lived. Using his wealth, he became a Cavalry Attendant, serving Emperor Wen. For ten years he received no promotion and was unknown. Shizhi said, “Serving in office for so long diminishes my brother’s property; this is not what I desire.” He wished to resign and return home. The Commandant of the Palace Attendants, Yuan Ang, knew him to be virtuous and regretted his departure, so he requested that Shizhi be transferred to fill a vacancy as a Herald. After Shizhi had completed the morning audience, he took the opportunity to discuss matters of current expediency. The Emperor said, “Keep it low-level; do not engage in overly high-minded theory. Make it something that can be implemented today.” Thereupon Shizhi spoke at length about affairs between the Qin and Han dynasties, why the Qin had lost and why the Han had risen. The Emperor praised him and appointed Shizhi as Vice Chief of the Heralds.

Shizhi accompanied the Emperor on a tour and ascended the Tiger Enclosure. The Emperor asked the Forester of the Imperial Park about the registers of various birds and beasts. After more than ten questions, the Forester looked left and right and could not answer. The Keeper of the Tiger Enclosure, standing nearby, answered the Emperor’s questions about the bird and beast registers in great detail, hoping to demonstrate his ability to respond fluently and endlessly. The Emperor said, “Should an official not be like this? The Forester is useless!” He then ordered Shizhi to appoint the Keeper as Director of the Imperial Park. Shizhi approached slowly and said, “Your Majesty, what kind of person was Zhou Bo, the Marquis of Jiang?” The Emperor said, “A man of integrity.” Shizhi asked again, “What kind of person was Zhang Xiangru, the Marquis of Dongyang?” The Emperor again said, “A man of integrity.” Shizhi said, “Zhou Bo and Zhang Xiangru are called men of integrity, yet these two could hardly speak when discussing matters. Should we not learn from this Keeper’s glib tongue and quick wit? Moreover, the Qin relied on officials who dealt with legal documents. Officials competed with one another in being swift and harsh in their scrutiny, but their flaw was merely formalistic compliance, lacking genuine compassion. As a result, their faults were never heard of, and the dynasty declined until the Second Emperor, when the world collapsed. Now, Your Majesty, because this Keeper is eloquent, you promote him beyond his rank. I fear that the world will follow suit, competing in eloquence without substance. Furthermore, the people’s transformation by their superiors is as swift as shadow and echo; your actions and decisions must not be unexamined.” The Emperor said, “Well said.” He stopped and did not appoint the Keeper.

The Emperor boarded his carriage, summoned Shizhi to ride beside him, and walked slowly, asking Shizhi about the flaws of the Qin. Shizhi answered with plain truth. Upon returning to the palace, the Emperor appointed Shizhi as Director of the Carriages and Horses.

Soon after, the Crown Prince and the King of Liang rode together in a carriage into the court and did not dismount at the Gate of the Commandant of the Guard. Shizhi pursued them and stopped the Crown Prince and the King of Liang, preventing them from entering the palace gates. He then impeached them for failing to dismount at the public gate, showing disrespect, and submitted the memorial. Empress Dowager Bo heard of this. Emperor Wen removed his cap and apologized, saying, “I have not disciplined my sons carefully.” Empress Dowager Bo then sent an envoy to convey the edict pardoning the Crown Prince and the King of Liang, after which they were allowed to enter. From this, Emperor Wen considered Shizhi extraordinary and appointed him as Central Great Master.

Soon after, he rose to the position of Commandant of the Palace Attendants. Accompanying the Emperor to the Baling Mausoleum, they stood to the north overlooking the toilet area. At that time, Lady Shen was accompanying them. The Emperor pointed out the road to Xinfeng to Lady Shen and said, “This is the route to Handan.” He had Lady Shen play the se, and leaning on the se, he sang himself. His mood was sorrowful and mournful. He looked at the courtiers and said, “Alas! If we use stones from Mount Bei for the outer coffin, fill the gaps with hemp floss and cut cinnabar lacquer, could it be moved?” Those around him said, “Well said.” Shizhi stepped forward and said, “If there is anything desirable inside, even if the South Mountain were sealed, there would still be gaps; if there is nothing desirable inside, even without a stone coffin, what is there to grieve?” The Emperor praised him. Later, Shizhi was appointed as Chief Justice.

Soon after, the Emperor went out to the Middle Wei Bridge. A person emerged from under the bridge, startling the Emperor’s carriage horses. The Emperor ordered cavalry to arrest him and handed him over to the Chief Justice. Shizhi investigated and questioned him. The man said, “A resident of the county came here, heard the imperial procession clearing the way, and hid under the bridge. After a long time, thinking the procession had passed, he came out, saw the imperial carriage and cavalry, and ran away.” The Chief Justice of Qin judged that for one person violating the imperial clearance, the penalty should be a fine. The Emperor was angry and said, “This person personally startled my horses. If my horses had not been gentle, and another horse had been startled, would it not have endangered me? Yet the Chief Justice only imposes a fine!” Shizhi said, “The law is what the Son of Heaven shares with the world. If the law is thus and we make it heavier, the law will lose credibility with the people. Moreover, at that moment, if Your Majesty had ordered immediate execution, that would have been the end. Now that it has been handed to the Chief Justice, the Chief Justice is the balance of the world. If it is tilted once, the application of law throughout the world will become inconsistent in severity, and where will the people place their hands and feet? I beg Your Majesty to consider this.” After a long time, the Emperor said, “The Chief Justice’s judgment is correct.”

Later, someone stole the jade ring from the front of the ancestral temple of Emperor Gao. The thief was caught. The Emperor was angry and handed the case to the Chief Justice for trial. Shizhi investigated the law regarding theft of ritual garments and imperial objects from the ancestral temple and submitted a memorial recommending the penalty of public execution. The Emperor was greatly angered and said, “How wicked! This person dared to steal the vessels of the Late Emperor. I handed him to the Chief Justice hoping to bring about his clan execution, yet you judge him according to the law. This is not my intention in reverently serving the ancestral temple.” Shizhi removed his cap and bowed his head to the ground, apologizing, saying, “The law is sufficient as it is. Moreover, for crimes of equal severity, the punishment varies according to the degree of opposition or compliance. If we execute the clan for stealing ancestral temple vessels, what if, by chance, a foolish commoner took a handful of earth from Changling Mausoleum? How would Your Majesty increase the punishment?” After a long time, the Emperor discussed it with the Empress Dowager, who then approved the Chief Justice’s judgment. At that time, the Commandant of the Capital, Marquis Tiaohou Zhou Yafu, and the Chancellor of Liang, Marquis Shandu Wang Tiankai, saw that Shizhi’s judgments were fair, and they formed close friendships with him. From this, the world praised Zhang Tingwei.

After Emperor Wen died, Emperor Jing ascended the throne. Shizhi was afraid and claimed illness. He wished to resign and leave, fearing a great purge; he wished to appear and apologize, but did not know how. Following the advice of Wang Sheng, he finally appeared and apologized. Emperor Jing did not reprimand him.

Wang Sheng was skilled in speaking about Huang-Lao philosophy and was a recluse. He had once been summoned to sit in the court. When the Three Excellencies and the Nine Ministers were all standing together, Wang Sheng, an old man, said, “My sandal strap is loose,” and looked at Zhang Tingwei, saying, “Tie my sandal strap for me!” Shizhi knelt and tied it for him. Afterward, someone said to Wang Sheng, “Why did you humiliate Zhang Tingwei in court, making him kneel to tie your sandal strap?” Wang Sheng said, “I am old and lowly, and I know I can ultimately do nothing to help Zhang Tingwei. Zhang Tingwei is currently a famous minister of the world. I deliberately humiliated him, making him kneel to tie my sandal strap, in order to enhance his reputation.” When the nobles heard this, they esteemed Wang Sheng and respected Zhang Tingwei.

Zhang Tingwei served Emperor Jing for over a year and was appointed Chancellor of the King of Huainan, still bearing the blame for his previous offense. After a long time, Shizhi died. His son was Zhang Zhi, with the courtesy name Changgong. He rose to the rank of Great Master but was dismissed. Because he could not curry favor with the contemporary powers, he never held office again in his lifetime.

Feng Tang’s grandfather was from Zhao. His father moved to Dai. When the Han dynasty rose, they moved to Anling. Tang was known for his filial piety and served as Chief of the Bureau of Palace Attendants, serving Emperor Wen. Once, when the Emperor’s carriage passed by, he asked Tang, “Old man, how did you become a Palace Attendant? Where is your home?” Tang answered truthfully. The Emperor said, “When I was in Dai, my Supervisor of Imperial Meals, Gao Qu, often spoke to me about the virtue of Li Qi, the general of Zhao, who fought below Julu. Now, every time I eat, I think of Julu. Do you know him?” Tang replied, “He is not as good as Lian Po and Li Mu as generals.” The Emperor said, “Why?” Tang said, “My grandfather, when in Zhao, served as a commander under Li Mu and was good friends with him. My father was formerly the Chancellor of Dai and was good friends with Li Qi, the general of Zhao, and knew his character.” After hearing about Lian Po and Li Mu, the Emperor was greatly pleased and slapped his thigh, saying, “Alas! If only I could have Lian Po or Li Mu as my general at this time! Would I not worry about the Xiongnu?” Tang said, “Your servant! Even if Your Majesty had Lian Po or Li Mu, you could not use them.” The Emperor was angry, rose, and entered the inner palace. After a long time, he summoned Tang to reprimand him, saying, “Why did you humiliate me in front of everyone? Is there no private place?” Tang apologized, saying, “This humble one does not know the taboos.”

At that time, the Xiongnu had recently invaded Chaona in large numbers, killing Bingyi, the Commandant of Beidi. The Emperor was concerned about the Hu raids and finally asked Tang again, “How do you know that I cannot use Lian Po and Li Mu?” Tang replied, “I have heard that in ancient times, when kings sent out generals, they would kneel and push the carriage wheel, saying, ‘Within the gates, I control; outside the gates, the general controls. Military merits and ranks are decided outside, and reported upon return. This is not empty talk.’ My grandfather said that when Li Mu was a general of Zhao stationed at the border, the rent from the military markets was used entirely to entertain the soldiers, and rewards were decided outside, without interference from the center. Entrusting them with responsibility and demanding success, Li Mu was able to exhaust his wisdom and ability. He dispatched 1,300 chariots, 13,000 archers, and 100,000 elite soldiers. With this, he drove back the Chanyu to the north, defeated the Donghu, destroyed the Danlin, suppressed the strong Qin in the west, and supported Han and Wei in the south. At that time, Zhao was nearly hegemonic. Later, when King Qian of Zhao ascended the throne, his mother was a courtesan. After King Qian ascended, he used the slander of Guo Kai and ultimately executed Li Mu, ordering Yan Ju to replace him. As a result, the army was defeated and the soldiers fled, and Zhao was captured and destroyed by Qin. Now, I secretly hear that Wei Shang, the Commandant of Yunzhong, uses all the rent from the military markets to entertain the soldiers, and spends his private money to feed them. Every five days he slaughters a cow to entertain guests, military officers, and retainers. As a result, the Xiongnu stay far away and do not approach the Yunzhong pass. Once the enemy entered, Shang led chariots and cavalry to attack them, killing many. The soldiers are all sons of common families, rising from the fields to join the army. How would they know the detailed records and unit codes? All day they fight hard, beheading enemies and capturing prisoners, and reporting their merits to the military headquarters. If one word does not correspond, legal officials use the law to punish them. Their rewards are not granted, but the officials’ application of the law is strictly enforced. I am foolish, but I think Your Majesty’s laws are too clear, rewards too light, and punishments too heavy. Moreover, Wei Shang, Commandant of Yunzhong, was punished for reporting six more enemy heads than the actual count. Your Majesty handed him to the officials, stripped his rank, and sentenced him to hard labor. From this, I say that even if Your Majesty had Lian Po or Li Mu, you could not use them. I am truly foolish and have violated taboos. Death, death!” The Emperor was pleased. That day, he ordered Feng Tang to carry the tally and pardon Wei Shang, restoring him as Commandant of Yunzhong, and appointed Tang as Commandant of Chariots and Cavalry, in charge of the Commandant of the Capital and the chariot and cavalry troops of the commanderies and kingdoms.

In the seventh year, Emperor Jing ascended the throne and appointed Tang as Chancellor of Chu, but he was dismissed. When Emperor Wu ascended, he sought virtuous men and Feng Tang was recommended. Tang was then over ninety years old and could not serve in office again, so Tang’s son, Feng Sui, was appointed as a Palace Attendant. Sui’s courtesy name was Wangsun. He was also an extraordinary man and was friendly with me.

The Grand Historian says: Zhang Ji’s words about men of integrity show that he followed the law without flattery. Feng Gong’s discussion of generals is profound! Profound! The saying goes, “If you do not know a person, look at his friends.” The praises of these two gentlemen can be recorded in the halls of government. The Book of Documents says, “Unbiased and unpartisan, the King’s Way is broad; unpartisan and unbiased, the King’s Way is smooth.” Zhang Ji and Feng Gong were close to this ideal. [end of text]


